### **Technical Details:** {#technical-details:}

- The course involved converting a SinglePlayer Game into a multiplayer one.   
- The final version has implemented **Lobby** and **Relay** services hosted on the *Unity Cloud.*  
- GameObjects are set up with a *NetworkObject* component and have their **MonoBehaviors** swapped out **NetworkBehaviors**.  
- For most manager classes Singletons are used. If there’s only one instance of it on the Network then we initialize them in Awake() but for objects like the PlayerPrefab we’re and a single local Instance exists **per client** we initialize it in On OnNetworkSpawn(). This makes sure the instance is only assigned when the prefab spawns in the server.  
- There was heavy use of **events;**  
- For synchronizing data across the network most of the data was sent and received via **ServerRpc** and **ClientRpc.**  
  - The most frequent configuration involved the client calling the ServerRpc, which then broadcast the data to corresponding ClientRpc that then executed the code locally for everyone including the original sender. *See illustrative example:*

- Since I didn’t want to spend a lot of time making the custom classes serializable to send them through the RPCs, data like the interacted cooking Item was stored in a global List or Dictionary and only the index was passed along. (ints are in fact serializable)  
- Then the receiver had to convert it back into its original class by accessing the Collection via the incoming index.  
  - Helper methods were made to help with this.  
- For behavior like p*layer animation* and *movement*, I left the **authority** to the **client**. Only behaviors like *Spawning, Destroying* (that HAVE to be done in the server anyways), *Gameplay Timers* and *Recipe orders* (That need to be centralized) were set up to be **server authoritative**.   
- **NetworkVariables** were used mostly because they all have an ***OnValueChange*** event. That fires at any point that the variable's value changes. Using the event was more flexible since we could listen for value changes but then decide if we were going to “actually use those events” to trigger anything. If so then the value was accessed.   
- Parenting was apparently impossible to do in NGO so I had to setup custom “copy transforms” behavior for holding and dropping items.

### **How to use:**  {#how-to-use:}

Disclaimer : (The build doesn’t seem to work unless i use one instance of the game running on the editor…)

1. **Main menu boots up** ,   
   1. Press the Play Button  
2. **This takes you to the Multiplayer scene**  
   1. If no Lobby’s are currently on the network then it should be empty like so:**![][image2]**  
   2. Run another build and with that one, press **Create Lobby**  
   3. A new window pops up, here you must first fill in a **name** for the lobby**![][image3]**  
      1. Creating a **Private Lobby** will create a private Lobby instance and take you to a new scene where you are given the:  
         1. Lobby name  
         2. Lobby code   
            1.  If another player is in the previous scene and adds that code to the black input field and presses “Join Code”  
            2. That player can now join your private Lobby

**![][image4]**

2. Creating a **Public Lobby** however makes it so the lobby will pop up in the Multiplayer menu. Clicking it will allow any player to join that Lobby.

**![][image5]**

3. QuickPlay will Join the first Public Lobby  
3. **A “Ready” button will appear:**  
   1. if all players in the lobby press ready then the game will shortly start  
4. **Here on the game scene you can choose to be either the Host Or the Client**  
   1. There can only be one host.  
   2. The game won’t work if there’s only Client’s. There needs to be at least one Host.  
5. **Play the game you have 90 seconds before the timer runs out.**

**Note:** The server only allows for connection when:

- The max of number of player (4) hasn’t been reached yet;  
- The game session hasn’t started.  
- The Lobby will timeout after 10 seconds if no other player joins.
